WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.952 align:middle line:90%
[SOFT INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC]

00:00:03.952 --> 00:00:30.134 align:middle line:90%


00:00:30.134 --> 00:00:33.646 align:middle line:84%
>> I feel like I'm working
and fighting every single day,

00:00:33.646 --> 00:00:35.020 align:middle line:84%
and I'm viewed as
a complete bum.

00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:38.988 align:middle line:90%


00:00:38.988 --> 00:00:40.590 align:middle line:90%
But that is my problem.

00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:43.622 align:middle line:84%
I cannot tell anyone
what is going on with me.

00:00:43.622 --> 00:00:48.050 align:middle line:90%


00:00:48.050 --> 00:00:51.550 align:middle line:84%
People see me act
quiet, and that's it.

00:00:51.550 --> 00:00:55.225 align:middle line:84%
But what is happening in
that quiet is completely--

00:00:55.225 --> 00:00:56.025 align:middle line:90%
it's just chaos.

00:00:56.025 --> 00:01:00.180 align:middle line:90%


00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:02.555 align:middle line:90%
I experience screaming voices.

00:01:02.555 --> 00:01:05.140 align:middle line:90%


00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:09.070 align:middle line:84%
I go into almost a
paralysis from fear--

00:01:09.070 --> 00:01:11.990 align:middle line:90%


00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:18.250 align:middle line:84%
just being absolutely
exhausted, and frustrated,

00:01:18.250 --> 00:01:21.310 align:middle line:90%
and just tired of--

00:01:21.310 --> 00:01:24.890 align:middle line:84%
tired of everything--
and just not

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:26.700 align:middle line:84%
wanting to fight
every single day.

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:29.250 align:middle line:90%


00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:33.690 align:middle line:84%
People don't believe
how insane I am.

00:01:33.690 --> 00:01:34.490 align:middle line:90%
Fuck!

00:01:34.490 --> 00:02:10.191 align:middle line:90%


00:02:10.191 --> 00:02:13.790 align:middle line:10%
>> At first, still has human
rights issues that took me

00:02:13.790 --> 00:02:18.710 align:middle line:10%
to tribal and indigenous
cultures around the world.

00:02:18.710 --> 00:02:20.720 align:middle line:84%
As a photographer,
I wanted to bring

00:02:20.720 --> 00:02:24.320 align:middle line:84%
viewers face to face with the
people who were struggling

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:27.140 align:middle line:84%
to hold on to their
unique way of life

00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:28.715 align:middle line:90%
and their traditional beliefs.

00:02:28.715 --> 00:02:32.870 align:middle line:90%


00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:36.170 align:middle line:84%
I became fascinated with
the remaining cultures that

00:02:36.170 --> 00:02:40.850 align:middle line:84%
commune with the spirits of
rivers, mountains, animals,

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:42.140 align:middle line:90%
and their ancestors.

00:02:42.140 --> 00:02:45.530 align:middle line:90%


00:02:45.530 --> 00:02:49.160 align:middle line:84%
While I was working in Northern
Kenya, I met [INAUDIBLE]..

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.250 align:middle line:84%
She was a 37-year-old
mother of five.

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:55.820 align:middle line:84%
When she was 13, she started
hearing voices and having

00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:59.360 align:middle line:84%
visions, said she was
feeling terrified.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:02.210 align:middle line:84%
But her grandmother took
her aside and told her

00:03:02.210 --> 00:03:05.040 align:middle line:84%
she had a very
special sensitivity,

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:08.330 align:middle line:84%
and then helped guide
her through her crisis.

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:11.620 align:middle line:84%
Today, she's a highly
respected healer and predictor

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:13.220 align:middle line:90%
in her Samburu tribe.

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:15.850 align:middle line:90%


00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:19.240 align:middle line:84%
Over the years, I've met
many people like [INAUDIBLE],,

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:23.050 align:middle line:84%
who could be labeled as crazy
in our culture but were seen

00:03:23.050 --> 00:03:25.150 align:middle line:90%
as gifted in their own--

00:03:25.150 --> 00:03:29.080 align:middle line:84%
people who transform their
mental and emotional crises

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:33.520 align:middle line:84%
to become healers or visionaries
for their communities.

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:37.090 align:middle line:84%
In the West, we often
call them Shaman.

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:38.770 align:middle line:10%
And I began to
wonder, could there

00:03:38.770 --> 00:03:42.520 align:middle line:10%
be something more to these
experiences we call crazy?

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:51.800 align:middle line:90%


00:03:51.800 --> 00:03:57.130 align:middle line:84%
When I was back home in Seattle,
I met a young man named Adam.

00:03:57.130 --> 00:03:58.910 align:middle line:90%
>> I was 20.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:04.540 align:middle line:84%
It was four days after my
20th birthday I went nuts.

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:08.547 align:middle line:84%
Very compassionate-- be
it animals, be it people--

00:04:08.547 --> 00:04:09.380 align:middle line:90%
at a very early age.

00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:11.790 align:middle line:90%
He was just really a happy baby.

00:04:11.790 --> 00:04:13.410 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely amazing.

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:16.380 align:middle line:84%
He's the funniest guy
you would ever know.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:19.769 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you've seen
that-- but hysterical-- totally

00:04:19.769 --> 00:04:21.779 align:middle line:90%
gifted athletically.

00:04:21.779 --> 00:04:23.810 align:middle line:90%
He rode a two-wheel bike at two.

00:04:23.810 --> 00:04:27.070 align:middle line:90%
At five, he got into karate.

00:04:27.070 --> 00:04:30.030 align:middle line:84%
>> He ended up as one of the
youngest kids to ever get his

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:33.675 align:middle line:84%
black belt. I think he
got that when he was 11.

00:04:33.675 --> 00:04:36.660 align:middle line:84%
>> So in high school when I
met Adam, I was 15; he was 16.

00:04:36.660 --> 00:04:40.500 align:middle line:84%
He had a cool, red Jeep
Wrangler, and he wakeboarded--

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:44.530 align:middle line:84%
and just really popular,
outgoing, charismatic guy--

00:04:44.530 --> 00:04:45.330 align:middle line:90%
lots of friends.

00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:48.300 align:middle line:84%
And he was always kind
of challenging the status

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:49.140 align:middle line:90%
quo so to speak.

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:51.350 align:middle line:84%
>> He just knew what
I was thinking a lot.

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:54.000 align:middle line:84%
I could be thinking of
something completely random,

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.150 align:middle line:84%
and he wouldn't
know it and tell me.

00:04:56.150 --> 00:04:57.900 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, it
would weird me out.

00:04:57.900 --> 00:04:59.680 align:middle line:84%
And I've heard that
from multiple people,

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:01.755 align:middle line:90%
too-- other friends of his.

00:05:01.755 --> 00:05:06.750 align:middle line:84%
>> I moved to Florida to pursue
professional wakeboarding.

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:09.750 align:middle line:84%
And in that period
is when I experienced

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:11.620 align:middle line:90%
that first depression.

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:14.910 align:middle line:90%
>> July 22nd, 2004--

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:16.190 align:middle line:90%
that was the date.

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:19.950 align:middle line:84%
He started telling us a math
equation that would solve

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:22.700 align:middle line:90%
all the family's problems.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:25.340 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't a very simple
one, but it made more sense

00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:27.480 align:middle line:84%
to him, which, of
course, to nobody else.

00:05:27.480 --> 00:05:31.130 align:middle line:84%
>> When it first occurred,
it was very fun and exciting.

00:05:31.130 --> 00:05:33.130 align:middle line:84%
It was just this
total shattering,

00:05:33.130 --> 00:05:36.380 align:middle line:84%
and my mind just opened,
and I started thinking

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:38.900 align:middle line:90%
of all these different things.

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:40.710 align:middle line:84%
And in that sense,
it was beautiful.

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:42.980 align:middle line:84%
I found it was the
first time I'd ever

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:47.810 align:middle line:84%
experienced a real
connection to the universe--

00:05:47.810 --> 00:05:50.720 align:middle line:84%
where I really felt
like a part of this--

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:52.610 align:middle line:90%
that I was this; this was me.

00:05:52.610 --> 00:05:55.700 align:middle line:90%
It was just like incredible.

00:05:55.700 --> 00:05:57.650 align:middle line:90%
Then I kept going.

00:05:57.650 --> 00:05:59.814 align:middle line:90%
And then I went way too far.

00:05:59.814 --> 00:06:00.730 align:middle line:90%
And then it got scary.

00:06:00.730 --> 00:06:03.290 align:middle line:90%
>> And it was terrifying--

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:05.645 align:middle line:84%
totally manic or
totally depressed.

00:06:05.645 --> 00:06:11.075 align:middle line:84%
>> The rage that will occur in
a manic episode is so scary.

00:06:11.075 --> 00:06:15.050 align:middle line:84%
>> You know, it's not who we
knew as happy Adam, funny Adam.

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:20.180 align:middle line:84%
And then you had this
Adam like [SNAP] that.

00:06:20.180 --> 00:06:24.440 align:middle line:84%
>> I was surprised to learn
how many people in the US will

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:29.050 align:middle line:84%
suffer from a psychological
crisis in their lifetime.

00:06:29.050 --> 00:06:31.010 align:middle line:10%
And like many of
the shaman I met,

00:06:31.010 --> 00:06:33.410 align:middle line:10%
the crisis happens
mostly in their youth.

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:37.260 align:middle line:90%


00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:39.510 align:middle line:84%
I met a young woman
in New York named

00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:43.260 align:middle line:84%
Ekhaya, who also had one of
these episodes in her 20s.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:46.300 align:middle line:84%
>> I didn't know what
was happening to me.

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:48.360 align:middle line:84%
I felt like my
whole world was just

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:51.570 align:middle line:84%
exploding like I was going
into a whole different reality

00:06:51.570 --> 00:06:53.560 align:middle line:90%
that I knew nothing about.

00:06:53.560 --> 00:06:56.090 align:middle line:84%
I was very afraid to
walk down the street

00:06:56.090 --> 00:06:59.180 align:middle line:84%
because I thought people
were all focused on me

00:06:59.180 --> 00:07:02.870 align:middle line:84%
and judging me, and I
thought everybody knew.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:06.290 align:middle line:84%
I had voices that would
tell me to cut myself.

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:09.470 align:middle line:84%
It was like the voices were
taking control over me.

00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:11.160 align:middle line:84%
The visions were
taking control over me.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:15.860 align:middle line:84%
I was very sensitive
to music, to sounds.

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:20.480 align:middle line:84%
I started to have very clear
visions of dead people--

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:23.030 align:middle line:84%
like just appearing
and watching me.

00:07:23.030 --> 00:07:28.560 align:middle line:84%
So I felt like I had eyes
watching me all the time.

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:31.780 align:middle line:84%
I started to see
my deceased father,

00:07:31.780 --> 00:07:35.360 align:middle line:90%
and he would show up in my room.

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:37.490 align:middle line:84%
And really, it was
the scariest thing

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:38.880 align:middle line:90%
that I've ever experienced.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:42.080 align:middle line:90%


00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:45.450 align:middle line:84%
I literally locked myself
in a room for months.

00:07:45.450 --> 00:07:48.330 align:middle line:84%
I took the light bulb
of a light fixture,

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:53.190 align:middle line:84%
and I became
completely enclosed.

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:59.496 align:middle line:90%


00:07:59.496 --> 00:08:03.600 align:middle line:84%
>> There was about a three-day
period of in my room,

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:06.990 align:middle line:84%
writing equations and
finding God in my notebook.

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:12.330 align:middle line:84%
And then finally, my parents
were like, whatcha doing?

00:08:12.330 --> 00:08:15.210 align:middle line:84%
And then I checked myself
into a mental institution.

00:08:15.210 --> 00:08:18.750 align:middle line:84%
That is not the
place to get sane.

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:20.495 align:middle line:84%
They put me in
this holding room.

00:08:20.495 --> 00:08:23.370 align:middle line:84%
And there was no door, and there
was a camera on the ceiling.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:25.620 align:middle line:84%
And I was just
laying on this bed,

00:08:25.620 --> 00:08:27.990 align:middle line:84%
and this little girl
walked into my room

00:08:27.990 --> 00:08:30.840 align:middle line:84%
and she was just
staring at me, just

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:33.150 align:middle line:90%
with this blank, bizarre stare.

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:35.730 align:middle line:84%
And I kept asking her to
leave, and she wouldn't.

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:40.020 align:middle line:84%
And there was more
crazy people everywhere,

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:43.240 align:middle line:84%
and they were able to
just come into my room.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:46.200 align:middle line:84%
I immediately felt
in danger and scared.

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:50.310 align:middle line:84%
And so I just
decided, no, and we

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:53.520 align:middle line:84%
went back to my parents'
house and just kind of tried

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:54.750 align:middle line:90%
to figure out what to do.

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:56.660 align:middle line:84%
They put me on
Depakote, and then

00:08:56.660 --> 00:09:01.050 align:middle line:84%
that just started the whole
process of, oh, no, now he's

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:01.860 align:middle line:90%
crying all day.

00:09:01.860 --> 00:09:02.920 align:middle line:90%
Let's feed him this one.

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:04.380 align:middle line:84%
Oh, no, now he's
barfing all day.

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:05.200 align:middle line:90%
Feed him this one.

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:09.210 align:middle line:84%
>> And we went from one doctor
to another doctor and one

00:09:09.210 --> 00:09:11.040 align:middle line:84%
prescription to
another prescription.

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:15.972 align:middle line:84%
>> He was on every medication,
I think, made for bipolar.

00:09:15.972 --> 00:09:19.530 align:middle line:84%
>> And they always say, well,
every brain is different.

00:09:19.530 --> 00:09:22.500 align:middle line:84%
Sorry if this makes
you crap your pants.

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:23.350 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it'll work.

00:09:23.350 --> 00:09:25.440 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it'll make
you kill yourself.

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:28.200 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the disclaimer
on these pills--

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:29.980 align:middle line:84%
that's typically the
first side effect--

00:09:29.980 --> 00:09:31.890 align:middle line:90%
is suicidal thoughts.

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:35.260 align:middle line:10%
And that's what the doctor's
giving you to feel better.

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:38.775 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's--
[LAUGHS] it's crazy.

00:09:38.775 --> 00:09:42.870 align:middle line:10%
>> Hearing of the struggles Adam
and Ekhaya were going through

00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:44.950 align:middle line:10%
made me want to learn more.

00:09:44.950 --> 00:09:46.950 align:middle line:84%
So I started
interviewing experts

00:09:46.950 --> 00:09:49.227 align:middle line:90%
in the field of mental health.

00:09:49.227 --> 00:09:51.810 align:middle line:84%
>> In the United States, we've
come to believe in the chemical

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:53.950 align:middle line:84%
imbalance theory of
mental disorders.

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:58.140 align:middle line:10%
So we believe that you
have some known deficiency

00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:01.980 align:middle line:10%
with the neurotransmitter,
and the drugs fix that,

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:03.930 align:middle line:10%
like insulin for diabetes.

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:07.350 align:middle line:10%
It was a valid
hypothesis that arose out

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:10.590 align:middle line:10%
of our understanding of how
the drugs acted on the brain,

00:10:10.590 --> 00:10:13.110 align:middle line:10%
and then it was investigated
and found out basically not

00:10:13.110 --> 00:10:14.220 align:middle line:10%
to be so.

00:10:14.220 --> 00:10:15.034 align:middle line:90%
I believed it.

00:10:15.034 --> 00:10:16.700 align:middle line:84%
When I was a reporter,
I wrote about it.

00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:18.830 align:middle line:84%
Our depression is
due to low serotonin.

00:10:18.830 --> 00:10:21.210 align:middle line:84%
Schizophrenia is due
to too much dopamine.

00:10:21.210 --> 00:10:23.610 align:middle line:84%
And I called up
some top researchers

00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:25.770 align:middle line:84%
and I said, I just want
to see the research that

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:28.030 align:middle line:84%
says you found that
people with schizophrenia

00:10:28.030 --> 00:10:30.060 align:middle line:84%
had too much
dopamine or you found

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:33.180 align:middle line:84%
that people with depression
had too little serotonin.

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:34.980 align:middle line:84%
And I'll never
forget the answer.

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:37.510 align:middle line:84%
The answer was, well,
we never found that.

00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:39.750 align:middle line:84%
I said, what do you mean
you never found that?

00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:43.060 align:middle line:84%
Oh, it's just a metaphor,
but it's not really true.

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:44.900 align:middle line:90%
Well, no, not really.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:46.406 align:middle line:90%
And I was stunned by that.

00:10:46.406 --> 00:10:49.590 align:middle line:84%
>> I am very much against
the casual and careless use

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:53.520 align:middle line:84%
of medication that characterizes
American society today.

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:56.670 align:middle line:84%
These medicines are very,
very powerful in helping,

00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:58.680 align:middle line:84%
but they can be very
powerful in harming.

00:10:58.680 --> 00:11:00.600 align:middle line:84%
Often the withdrawn
problems will be worse

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:01.766 align:middle line:90%
than the original condition.

00:11:01.766 --> 00:11:04.800 align:middle line:84%
>> I can look at any clinic I've
worked at, and if they've been

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:06.600 align:middle line:84%
in the clinic for
15 or 20 years,

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:10.230 align:middle line:84%
they've been on every
category of antipsychotic

00:11:10.230 --> 00:11:11.070 align:middle line:90%
in the process.

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:14.280 align:middle line:84%
And the truth is that they
still have the same symptoms.

00:11:14.280 --> 00:11:15.930 align:middle line:84%
They still have the
same side effects.

00:11:15.930 --> 00:11:17.820 align:middle line:84%
They still are operating
at the same level.

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:20.932 align:middle line:84%
They may have been hospitalized
five, six, 10 times

00:11:20.932 --> 00:11:21.765 align:middle line:90%
during that process.

00:11:21.765 --> 00:11:26.280 align:middle line:10%
>> We've been primed to believe
that, with medical research,

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:30.450 align:middle line:10%
we can find the causes of things
and that we can create these

00:11:30.450 --> 00:11:32.580 align:middle line:10%
magic bullets that
fix these problems.

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:36.240 align:middle line:10%
So it fit into that larger
story of medical progress

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:37.640 align:middle line:10%
that we believe in.

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:39.430 align:middle line:10%
We've been embracing
this paradigm of care

00:11:39.430 --> 00:11:41.640 align:middle line:10%
now for almost 30
years, and we've

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:43.830 align:middle line:10%
seen the burden go
up, and up, and up.

00:11:43.830 --> 00:11:45.810 align:middle line:84%
And if you have an
effective medical treatment

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:48.630 align:middle line:84%
for a disease, at the very
least, that burden of disease

00:11:48.630 --> 00:11:51.730 align:middle line:84%
should hopefully stay
stable or even go down.

00:11:51.730 --> 00:11:53.758 align:middle line:84%
And we're seeing
exactly the opposite.

00:11:53.758 --> 00:11:56.964 align:middle line:90%


00:11:56.964 --> 00:11:59.140 align:middle line:90%
>> I didn't know why I was here.

00:11:59.140 --> 00:11:59.940 align:middle line:90%
I had no purpose.

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:02.960 align:middle line:90%


00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:04.990 align:middle line:84%
I didn't think I had
any reason to breathe.

00:12:04.990 --> 00:12:12.070 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't feel deserving
of love, of anything.

00:12:12.070 --> 00:12:16.540 align:middle line:84%
The first suicide attempt was,
I took a whole bottle of pills.

00:12:16.540 --> 00:12:20.140 align:middle line:84%
The second attempt
was me walking out

00:12:20.140 --> 00:12:23.650 align:middle line:84%
of the house headed into
a busy street traffic.

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:26.746 align:middle line:84%
I just wanted a car to hit me,
or a truck, or just something

00:12:26.746 --> 00:12:28.120 align:middle line:84%
to take me out,
because this time

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:30.160 align:middle line:90%
I wanted it to really work.

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:32.750 align:middle line:84%
I always felt like
I was the problem.

00:12:32.750 --> 00:12:36.340 align:middle line:84%
And if I could get
rid of the problem,

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:39.040 align:middle line:90%
everyone else would be OK.

00:12:39.040 --> 00:12:42.470 align:middle line:84%
I decided to try to
get some kind of help.

00:12:42.470 --> 00:12:45.070 align:middle line:84%
And I was in the hospital
for about six weeks.

00:12:45.070 --> 00:12:47.860 align:middle line:84%
I was put on several different
medications-- heavy drugs,

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:53.740 align:middle line:84%
anti-psychotics, and it really
changed who I was completely.

00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:58.930 align:middle line:84%
I gained 70 pounds in the
first 2 and 1/2 months.

00:12:58.930 --> 00:12:59.920 align:middle line:90%
I just felt drugged up.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:04.910 align:middle line:90%


00:13:04.910 --> 00:13:08.290 align:middle line:84%
>> I felt like a lab rat, and
the side effects were just

00:13:08.290 --> 00:13:10.600 align:middle line:90%
awful, absolutely awful--

00:13:10.600 --> 00:13:12.290 align:middle line:90%
vomiting all day--

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:16.240 align:middle line:84%
I couldn't leave my house
for so long from just

00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:18.370 align:middle line:84%
like these awful
anxiety attacks.

00:13:18.370 --> 00:13:21.405 align:middle line:84%
And the thought of
interacting with people

00:13:21.405 --> 00:13:22.780 align:middle line:84%
would make me sick
to my stomach.

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:26.830 align:middle line:10%
>> I was the only one
who he could be around.

00:13:26.830 --> 00:13:31.840 align:middle line:84%
>> She basically terminated
her job and made it a full-time

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:33.610 align:middle line:84%
responsibility to
take care of him.

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:38.770 align:middle line:10%
>> It took five or six years
to get him where he could go

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:39.715 align:middle line:10%
to work.

00:13:39.715 --> 00:13:44.050 align:middle line:84%
>> You go through the
whole gauntlet from,

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:45.490 align:middle line:90%
was I a good father?

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:47.380 align:middle line:90%
Did I cause this?

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:49.155 align:middle line:90%
Did we do something as parents?

00:13:49.155 --> 00:13:51.850 align:middle line:84%
And the pain that you
see him going through

00:13:51.850 --> 00:13:54.640 align:middle line:84%
and the inability to
do anything to help it

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:56.265 align:middle line:90%
are the toughest things.

00:13:56.265 --> 00:13:58.780 align:middle line:90%
>> I had no idea who I was.

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:02.170 align:middle line:84%
I lost myself, my identity,
my friends, my family.

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:03.958 align:middle line:90%
I lost everything.

00:14:03.958 --> 00:14:05.950 align:middle line:90%
[CHIME]

00:14:05.950 --> 00:14:08.910 align:middle line:84%
>> After four years of
horrible side effects,

00:14:08.910 --> 00:14:12.120 align:middle line:84%
Adam quit all his meds at
once, which I've learned is

00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:14.070 align:middle line:90%
a dangerous thing to do.

00:14:14.070 --> 00:14:18.310 align:middle line:84%
And then he did a 10-day
silent meditation retreat.

00:14:18.310 --> 00:14:25.710 align:middle line:84%
>> I went there a drug-addict
alcoholic that hated everyone

00:14:25.710 --> 00:14:32.400 align:middle line:84%
and came back a sober,
life-loving vegan,

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:34.410 align:middle line:90%
complete health nut--

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:37.280 align:middle line:90%
like, no one knew who I was.

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:41.770 align:middle line:84%
>> There was an obvious, major
change in his serenity and his

00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:42.570 align:middle line:90%
peace of mind.

00:14:42.570 --> 00:14:44.670 align:middle line:90%
>> [SINGING] I'm a simple man.

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:46.980 align:middle line:90%
>> He quit everything.

00:14:46.980 --> 00:14:51.720 align:middle line:84%
He was a smoker, a drinker,
pot smoking, and the meds--

00:14:51.720 --> 00:14:54.510 align:middle line:84%
and he went to that
10-day meditation--

00:14:54.510 --> 00:14:55.850 align:middle line:90%
cold turkey on everything.

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:57.060 align:middle line:90%
I can't believe he did that.

00:14:57.060 --> 00:14:59.970 align:middle line:84%
>> Looking back at it, now I
really wish that I would have

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:03.420 align:middle line:84%
known these things and
tried the homeopathic,

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:06.330 align:middle line:84%
meditative approach first,
but it was just kind of like

00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:08.910 align:middle line:90%
a panic, I don't know--

00:15:08.910 --> 00:15:11.790 align:middle line:84%
put some medication in this
kid and just hope for the best.

00:15:11.790 --> 00:15:19.550 align:middle line:90%


00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:22.810 align:middle line:10%
>> While doing a human
rights story on Tibet,

00:15:22.810 --> 00:15:26.560 align:middle line:10%
I had the rare opportunity
to witness a young monk,

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:31.390 align:middle line:10%
known as a kuten, go into trance
and channel the state oracle

00:15:31.390 --> 00:15:34.030 align:middle line:10%
of Tibet.

00:15:34.030 --> 00:15:37.720 align:middle line:84%
The ceremony took place in a
monastery near the Dalai Lama's

00:15:37.720 --> 00:15:40.900 align:middle line:90%
residence.

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:44.440 align:middle line:84%
Shortly after they seated
him, his eyes rolled back,

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:48.610 align:middle line:84%
and he began speaking
in a high-pitched voice.

00:15:48.610 --> 00:15:50.590 align:middle line:90%
Suddenly, he collapsed.

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:52.810 align:middle line:84%
And as they carried
him out of the room,

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:56.290 align:middle line:84%
I was left wondering
what happened.

00:15:56.290 --> 00:15:59.890 align:middle line:84%
Two days later, I was invited
to interview the kuten.

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:01.720 align:middle line:90%
His name was Thupten.

00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:03.970 align:middle line:90%
He was 30 years old at the time.

00:16:03.970 --> 00:16:08.560 align:middle line:84%
He said he began having intense
dreams, severe mood swings,

00:16:08.560 --> 00:16:12.400 align:middle line:84%
hearing voices, and
thought he might be dying.

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:15.100 align:middle line:84%
The older monks recognized
he had the potential

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:17.395 align:middle line:90%
to become a kuten.

00:16:17.395 --> 00:16:19.655 align:middle line:10%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:16:19.655 --> 00:16:47.796 align:middle line:90%


00:16:47.796 --> 00:16:53.290 align:middle line:84%
>> We're so locked into our
mind in the rational world,

00:16:53.290 --> 00:16:58.270 align:middle line:84%
in the scientific world, that
when we have the spiritual

00:16:58.270 --> 00:17:02.290 align:middle line:84%
experience, it can literally
blow somebody's mind,

00:17:02.290 --> 00:17:04.119 align:middle line:84%
and they don't know
what to do with it.

00:17:04.119 --> 00:17:08.829 align:middle line:84%
And what's needed instead of
stigmatizing people and giving

00:17:08.829 --> 00:17:12.610 align:middle line:84%
them labels is to
give people tools

00:17:12.610 --> 00:17:17.980 align:middle line:84%
to learn how to ground and
to work with these expanded

00:17:17.980 --> 00:17:19.259 align:middle line:90%
states of consciousness.

00:17:19.259 --> 00:17:24.970 align:middle line:84%
>> For some people, they can
be an opening to a deeper

00:17:24.970 --> 00:17:28.300 align:middle line:84%
self-understanding, to deeper
psychological knowledge,

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:31.030 align:middle line:90%
or to spiritual realms.

00:17:31.030 --> 00:17:33.150 align:middle line:84%
>> According to the research,
the best place to be

00:17:33.150 --> 00:17:36.550 align:middle line:84%
a schizophrenic in the world is
not North America with all its

00:17:36.550 --> 00:17:37.970 align:middle line:90%
pharmacopeia.

00:17:37.970 --> 00:17:40.910 align:middle line:84%
It's actually a village
in Africa or India

00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:43.270 align:middle line:84%
where there's
acceptance, where people

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:45.630 align:middle line:84%
make room for your
differentness,

00:17:45.630 --> 00:17:49.104 align:middle line:84%
where connection is not
broken but is maintained,

00:17:49.104 --> 00:17:50.770 align:middle line:84%
where you're not
excluded and ostracized

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:52.987 align:middle line:84%
but where you're
welcomed, and where

00:17:52.987 --> 00:17:55.570 align:middle line:84%
there's room for you to act out
whatever you need to act out--

00:17:55.570 --> 00:17:57.739 align:middle line:84%
or to express whatever
you need to express.

00:17:57.739 --> 00:17:59.780 align:middle line:84%
And the whole community
might even sing with you,

00:17:59.780 --> 00:18:02.440 align:middle line:84%
or chant with you,
or hold ceremony.

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:07.300 align:middle line:84%
Meaning-- find some meaning in
your quote unquote "craziness."

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:10.910 align:middle line:10%
>> As our film progressed, we
began hearing from people who

00:18:10.910 --> 00:18:13.850 align:middle line:10%
identified themselves
as survivors--

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:17.540 align:middle line:10%
meaning survivors of our
mental health care system.

00:18:17.540 --> 00:18:20.810 align:middle line:84%
Many had come out from the
shadows of their diagnosis

00:18:20.810 --> 00:18:23.960 align:middle line:84%
and labels by meeting
each other online

00:18:23.960 --> 00:18:28.910 align:middle line:84%
to share their experiences
and to form support groups.

00:18:28.910 --> 00:18:32.930 align:middle line:84%
Will Hall is on the forefront
of what is called the recovery

00:18:32.930 --> 00:18:33.785 align:middle line:90%
movement.

00:18:33.785 --> 00:18:36.080 align:middle line:84%
>> When I first
was hospitalized,

00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:41.180 align:middle line:84%
I was feeling so desperate
that I wanted to die.

00:18:41.180 --> 00:18:42.590 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to kill myself.

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:45.540 align:middle line:84%
And I was hearing very,
very aggressive voices,

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:48.695 align:middle line:84%
and I ended up walking to
the Golden Gate Bridge.

00:18:48.695 --> 00:18:52.475 align:middle line:84%
And I remember dragging my arm
against the chain-link fence,

00:18:52.475 --> 00:18:54.770 align:middle line:90%
and my fingers were bloody.

00:18:54.770 --> 00:18:59.060 align:middle line:84%
And when I got to the
bridge and I looked down,

00:18:59.060 --> 00:19:01.700 align:middle line:84%
I really felt like I
needed to end my life.

00:19:01.700 --> 00:19:05.100 align:middle line:10%
I felt like I was
this complete failure.

00:19:05.100 --> 00:19:07.520 align:middle line:84%
So I was in really
bad, bad shape.

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:11.570 align:middle line:84%
And the mental health
system only made that worse.

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:13.560 align:middle line:84%
I went to the clinic
in San Francisco.

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:15.560 align:middle line:84%
My therapist had recommended
that maybe I should

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:17.840 align:middle line:90%
try different medications.

00:19:17.840 --> 00:19:19.580 align:middle line:84%
And I was buzzed
into the clinic.

00:19:19.580 --> 00:19:21.740 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't know
what was coming,

00:19:21.740 --> 00:19:23.210 align:middle line:90%
but the door locked behind me.

00:19:23.210 --> 00:19:27.020 align:middle line:84%
It was like there was this wild
animal that they had captured,

00:19:27.020 --> 00:19:28.310 align:middle line:90%
and they were evaluating it.

00:19:28.310 --> 00:19:31.880 align:middle line:84%
And I was put in restraints,
and I was not resisting,

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:34.280 align:middle line:90%
or arguing, or being hostile.

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:36.110 align:middle line:84%
Finally, after doing
all these tests,

00:19:36.110 --> 00:19:39.920 align:middle line:84%
the resident psychiatrists
who had been working with me

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:41.060 align:middle line:90%
came in and sat down.

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:44.540 align:middle line:84%
They said, OK, Mr. Hall, we
have your results of this test.

00:19:44.540 --> 00:19:46.065 align:middle line:90%
We have your diagnosis.

00:19:46.065 --> 00:19:51.020 align:middle line:84%
It was this very solemn,
ceremonial moment.

00:19:51.020 --> 00:19:55.070 align:middle line:84%
And they said, you have
a severe mental illness.

00:19:55.070 --> 00:19:58.790 align:middle line:84%
You have a kind of
schizophrenia called

00:19:58.790 --> 00:20:00.950 align:middle line:90%
schizoaffective disorder.

00:20:00.950 --> 00:20:04.070 align:middle line:84%
It combines the criteria
for schizophrenia

00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:06.720 align:middle line:84%
with the criteria
for bipolar disorder.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:09.609 align:middle line:84%
So it's kind of like
this catchall diagnosis.

00:20:09.609 --> 00:20:11.150 align:middle line:84%
It's sort of like
winning the lottery

00:20:11.150 --> 00:20:12.900 align:middle line:90%
of severe mental illness.

00:20:12.900 --> 00:20:15.299 align:middle line:90%
And they said, there's no cure.

00:20:15.299 --> 00:20:16.340 align:middle line:90%
There's no cure for this.

00:20:16.340 --> 00:20:19.820 align:middle line:84%
You will be maintaining
yourself on medication

00:20:19.820 --> 00:20:21.620 align:middle line:90%
to manage your symptoms.

00:20:21.620 --> 00:20:24.860 align:middle line:84%
We really recommend that you
rethink some of your goals

00:20:24.860 --> 00:20:26.240 align:middle line:90%
in your life.

00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:30.260 align:middle line:84%
That moment was really
like casting a spell on me.

00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:34.040 align:middle line:84%
And they were in the
process of transforming me

00:20:34.040 --> 00:20:38.030 align:middle line:84%
from an ordinary,
full human being

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:41.690 align:middle line:84%
into the second-class citizen
of being a mental patient.

00:20:41.690 --> 00:20:44.360 align:middle line:90%


00:20:44.360 --> 00:20:47.810 align:middle line:84%
>> I interviewed a group of
people that had been diagnosed

00:20:47.810 --> 00:20:50.930 align:middle line:84%
for their mental emotional
distress and asked each

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:53.130 align:middle line:84%
of them, what was
your diagnosis.

00:20:53.130 --> 00:20:57.640 align:middle line:84%
>> Schizophrenia, schizotypal,
schizoid personality,

00:20:57.640 --> 00:21:01.710 align:middle line:84%
schizoaffective, bipolar
I and bipolar II.

00:21:01.710 --> 00:21:06.590 align:middle line:84%
>> ADD, dysthymia,
depression, and PTSD.

00:21:06.590 --> 00:21:10.670 align:middle line:84%
>> Borderline personality,
they put autism,

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:17.160 align:middle line:84%
they put Asperger's, they
put manic depressive--

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:18.290 align:middle line:90%
I didn't think I was that.

00:21:18.290 --> 00:21:22.460 align:middle line:84%
>> Manic depression,
bipolar, bipolar I,

00:21:22.460 --> 00:21:24.340 align:middle line:84%
and just one time
schizoaffective.

00:21:24.340 --> 00:21:29.060 align:middle line:84%
>> In the era of the DSM-3,
there were like 12 personality

00:21:29.060 --> 00:21:32.180 align:middle line:84%
disorders, and I
had eight of them.

00:21:32.180 --> 00:21:39.330 align:middle line:84%
And the perfectionist in me
wanted to try and get all 12.

00:21:39.330 --> 00:21:42.610 align:middle line:10%
>> I learned that all these
diagnoses come from a book

00:21:42.610 --> 00:21:47.200 align:middle line:10%
called The DSM, the Diagnostic
and Statistical Manual

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:51.130 align:middle line:10%
of Mental Disorders published
by the American Psychiatric

00:21:51.130 --> 00:21:53.380 align:middle line:10%
Association.

00:21:53.380 --> 00:21:55.900 align:middle line:84%
Over the years, the
number of disorders

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:58.705 align:middle line:84%
has increased dramatically
with each new addition.

00:21:58.705 --> 00:22:04.190 align:middle line:90%


00:22:04.190 --> 00:22:08.350 align:middle line:84%
>> The problem with the DSM-5
is it took a number of normal

00:22:08.350 --> 00:22:11.080 align:middle line:84%
aspects of life and
pathologized them--

00:22:11.080 --> 00:22:14.340 align:middle line:84%
normal grief because
major depressive disorder.

00:22:14.340 --> 00:22:17.050 align:middle line:84%
Overeating becomes
binge eating disorder.

00:22:17.050 --> 00:22:19.520 align:middle line:84%
Temper tantrums become
disruptive mood dysregulation

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:20.320 align:middle line:90%
disorder.

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:26.500 align:middle line:90%


00:22:26.500 --> 00:22:29.090 align:middle line:84%
It's taking the experiences
of everyday life

00:22:29.090 --> 00:22:31.310 align:middle line:84%
that are unavoidable, part
of the human condition,

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:33.172 align:middle line:84%
turning them into
medical disorders.

00:22:33.172 --> 00:22:36.680 align:middle line:84%
>> The Diagnostic and
Statistical Manual is basically

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:39.950 align:middle line:84%
a sophisticated way of
not listening to people.

00:22:39.950 --> 00:22:43.130 align:middle line:84%
You interview just so that
you've heard certain keywords,

00:22:43.130 --> 00:22:44.990 align:middle line:84%
you fit it into your
framework, and then

00:22:44.990 --> 00:22:46.880 align:middle line:84%
you've got a whole
algorithm of treatments

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:48.620 align:middle line:84%
that you offer
people so that when

00:22:48.620 --> 00:22:51.990 align:middle line:84%
your colleagues and your
supervisors ask you,

00:22:51.990 --> 00:22:53.580 align:middle line:84%
what are you doing
to this person?

00:22:53.580 --> 00:22:54.830 align:middle line:90%
You're following the protocol.

00:22:54.830 --> 00:22:58.910 align:middle line:84%
>> If we used all
these psychiatric tests

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:03.470 align:middle line:84%
on the healthy population, I
doubt that anyone would avoid

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:06.650 align:middle line:90%
to get at least one diagnosis.

00:23:06.650 --> 00:23:10.010 align:middle line:84%
We think that there are people
who are normal over here,

00:23:10.010 --> 00:23:11.930 align:middle line:84%
and then there's the
pathological ones who

00:23:11.930 --> 00:23:15.500 align:middle line:84%
have depression, or anxiety,
or addiction, or schizophrenia,

00:23:15.500 --> 00:23:20.144 align:middle line:84%
bipolar disorder, ADHD, or any
number of other conditions.

00:23:20.144 --> 00:23:26.080 align:middle line:90%


00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:28.690 align:middle line:90%
What I see is a continuum.

00:23:28.690 --> 00:23:30.500 align:middle line:84%
These traits, to one
degree or another,

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:33.320 align:middle line:90%
are present in almost everybody.

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:36.370 align:middle line:84%
And it's a mythology to
think that there's the normal

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:37.620 align:middle line:90%
and then there's the abnormal.

00:23:37.620 --> 00:23:40.302 align:middle line:90%


00:23:40.302 --> 00:23:42.700 align:middle line:84%
>> Three months
into our filming,

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:45.220 align:middle line:90%
Adam asked to be interviewed.

00:23:45.220 --> 00:23:48.910 align:middle line:84%
He had just started his fourth
10day meditation retreat,

00:23:48.910 --> 00:23:53.020 align:middle line:84%
